post_text: Central High School would like to give a huge THANK YOU to Andre Irizarry and the Swing 4 Sydney Foundation for their very generous $1500 donation to our Lifesavers Program. Andre and his team have been instrumental in bringing this program to Central and we are blessed to have them as partners. The Central High School LifeSavers are a peer-support suicide and crisis-prevention student group designed to help teenagers cope healthfully with the challenges of drugs and alcohol, peer and family relationships, academic problems, anxiety, and suicide. LifeSavers is a recognized student organization in high schools that have chosen to be pro-active in caring for their student population.

post_text:
Good Morning!!

Registration for all freshman and transfer students will take place in the Main Office from 8AM to 3PM on August 4-5 and from 8AM to 7PM on August 6th.

Online Registration will begin for all returning (10th - 12th grade) students on Tuesday, August 4th. Directions for how to register your child through the Qmlative Family Access Portal can be found on our website - www.centralcougars.org - under "Cougar News." The registration process and fee payment will need to be completed by 3:00PM on Friday, August 7th.

If parents would prefer to pay their fees with cash or check, please stop by the main office sometime between 8AM to 3PM on August 4th - 6th.

Finally, please understand that this is a new process for Central and we will be learning right along with all of our parents. Please contact us with any questions or problems you have with the Online registration process and we will do our very best to help.

Thanks!!

Please find important information in regards to the Central High School Virtual Graduation Ceremony and the last #bethelight event below:

Class of 2020 Virtual Graduation Reminder and Link:

*The following link will allow you to access the virtual ceremony beginning at 7:00pm: https://youtu.be/Nxyw8cShvdk
*The YouTube link will go live at 7:00pm tomorrow (Thursday) evening, May 28th, and for planning purposes, the virtual event is approximately 1 hour in length.

Final #bethelight Remembrance Event:

*The Central High School football stadium lights will turn on for a final time this school year tomorrow (Thursday) evening, May 28th, as a tribute to the Class of 2020. The lights on Astroth Field will come on at 8:20pm and turn off at 8:40pm. We will play music during this brief event as well so feel free to stop by Central tomorrow night after viewing your Virtual Graduation and enjoy the final #bethelight event for the Class of 2020!
Thanks and we wish you all a safe and enjoyable summer!!*

Per the governor's announcement this afternoon, the Central Community High School building closure has been extended through the end of the school year. E-Learning and food distribution will continue through May 27th, 2020 and we will finish strong!

Additional information will be shared soon, particularly regarding plans for prom, graduation, athletics, awards ceremonies, and more. Thank you for your continued patience and understanding as we navigate these ever-changing times.

post_text: Like all of the phenomenal teachers and support staff at Central, Coach Peters has been working extremely hard to meet the needs of his students during the closure. Coach is at the school every morning, before 7AM, planning and preparing lessons for our Cougars. He truly loves and misses his students. KP is a 30+ year teaching veteran who has been willing to develop and implement an entirely new style of instruction. He is a shining example of the dedication, passion, and professionalism that can be found throughout Central High School. Our folks are ALL IN ALL THE TIME and we could not be prouder of their work. #imaginegreatness #buildingabetterworld #AIATT

Central Community High School is joining the national #bethelight campaign on Friday nights. The lights on Robert J. Astroth Field will be turned on at 8:20PM (20:20 Military Time) and left on for 20 minutes each Friday. Seniors, we are participating in this event to pay tribute to you.

We will be shining our lights in recognition of our phenomenal Class of 2020!! #imaginegreatness #buildingabetterworld #cougarnation

Feel free to swing by the school and check out the lights, take pictures, and make memories - but please do not congregate or get out of your vehicles #sorry.

Thank you for your continued support, patience, and understanding.

post_text:
Two of our senior students, Mackenzie Duncan and Serena Voss, have created an Instagram page called “centralcougars2020decisions." They are using this page to post information about the Central High School Class of 2020. Senior students are encouraged to send their information to Mackenzie or Serena via email (mduncan@centralcougar.org or svoss@centralcougars.org) and they will be featured on the CentralCougars2020decisions account!!

Feel free to answeres to these questions in your email:
1. What are your future plans?
2. What are your favorite memories of the senior class?
3. What are you thankful for? Please let us know the people and actions.
4. What advice you would like to give to the senior class as a whole?

You can respond with a video, a picture, or a small blurb/ paragraph!

Great job Mackenzie and Serena!! Central appreciates you organizing such an AWESOME activity!!

Please check out Kaitlyn Brown's #mystory and AWESOME artwork below!! Thank you for the inspiring message, Kaitlyn!! Outstanding Job!!
___________________

Besides work, during this quarantine, I have had time to finish some of my paintings and start some new ones:)

“Love me for who I am, not who you want me to be” is a quote I live by. It has and forever will be my favorite quote. I want people to love me and love my personality the way I am, not the way that society wants me to be. I am my own unique person. I want to be loved for my differences. Also, sunflowers are my favorite flowers and I wanted to do something a little different, therefore today I painted the sunflower red. (Which is still real, but it is more rare of course) . I hope you are staying healthy and staying safe. @ Central Comm High School

post_text:
As always, Coach Short has been busy leaving people, places, and things BETTER than he found them. Please check out his awsome #My Story below. Awesome work, Coach and the Walsh Brothers!! #imaginegreatness
_________
After being motivated by several Facebook posts and a challenge Coach Howard made to the track team, I decided to take my oldest daughter Ava out to pick up some trash along Highway 161 heading from Albers to Germantown. As we were about two bags in, I heard a big truck pull up and saw the Walsh boys hop out. They were on their way to Bartelso and their Dad had them help until he came back through. We filled up 4 trash bags. After we ran out of bags, we piled up enough trash to fill two more bags! It was a great experience to teach my daughter about the importance of volunteering to help your community. The best lesson she learned though was some of the worst jobs in the world are more enjoyable when some friends show up to help! Thank you to the Walsh family for the boost in man power!

post_text:
Molly Detmer has stayed busy while practicing social distancing. She completed this amazing "home improvment" project and we are super impressed with her creativity!! Please check out Molly's artwork and #mystory below!! Way to go, Molly!!

________________________________
As I sat in my room, staring at my blank wall, thinking about how much I miss my classes and teachers, an idea popped into my head. Although I miss every hour of the school day, in particular I miss Art. But, a sketch book or small canvas just wasn’t cutting it for me anymore. So, I broke the laws of go big or go home, because I have to respect social distancing, and did both. I went big, and stayed home, and got to be a little artsy too.

post_text:
At the 2:30PM press conference, the State of Illinois announced that the mandatory school building closure will be extended through April 30th, 2020. I know this is disappointing news to our students, teachers, parents, and staff, but please try to stay positive and encourage your students to make the best of this eLearning opportunity. One final thought, in the words of Carrie Hruby, "Public education has always been bigger than bricks and mortar. For the first time in history, we can see the way schools extend into homes. Parents and educators are partners now more than ever. Our buildings may be closed, but school is open." Our love and care for students will continue throughout the building closure and we absolutely cherish the support we have received from our parents. You all are simply the best. #imaginegreatness
--
Dr. Dustin Foutch
Superintendent, Central Community High School
It's Great to be a Cougar!!
#imaginegreatness

post_text: The media center will now start delivering library books! The process is simple. Email Mrs. Hogg (bhogg@centralcougars.org) with your book requests, and she will check out your requested books and deliver them directly to your front porch every Wednesday. You can find the library's online catalog by going to the media center's website and clicking on the stack of books. Once you conduct your search, you will be able to limit your search to books available at Central High School. You will not be able to request books from other libraries because the Illinois Heartland Library System has suspended delivery, but anything that is in Central's media center will be available. Please contact Mrs. Hogg with any questions you may have about this process.

Good Morning!!

Please click the link below to view a Cougar Newscast outlining Phase 2 of Central High School’s eLearning Plan. This plan is set to go in effect from March 31st through April 7th. We hope that our students will be able to return on April 8th and we will go back to learning in a traditional, face-to-face format, but we have also created plans to address a longer mandated school closing, if needed. We would like to emphasize that the state has not made the decision to implement a longer school closure, but we have to plan for the worst and pray for the best.

Also, for further clarification in regards to the Final Exam Incentive mentioned in the video, students will be exempt from exams if they have perfect attendance for all remaining attendance days either through eLearning or face-to-face instruction.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GVT-BOG_hv0&t=336s

post_text:
The Drafting Competition Results From the Regional Contest!!

Central had winners in multiple areas of Drafting. In the Board Drafting Divisions the Cougars had two third place medalists, Travis Eversgerd and Karlie Markus - they worked diligently to draw mechanical blocks and two story houses with precision and linework. In the area of Machine CAD the block was designed by Chris Mueller who earned a 2nd place medal and a chance to represent the Cougars at the state drafting competition. Four more medal winners at Central who earned their opportunity to compete at the state drafting competition in the 3D Cad Modeling area included Justin Hulesmann placing first. In 3D architectural drafting Cole Winkeler placed 2nd and created a two story house. Kyle Athmer was the final medalist in architectural 2D drafting. Congratulations to everyone on the drafting team and good luck at State next month!

post_text:
Huge Congrats to our very own Mrs. Weh!!

Mrs. Weh recently received the Southern Illinois Community Support Services Advocacy Award for making a difference in the lives of people with intellectual and developmental disabilities.

Mrs. Weh received the 2019 Advocacy Award for organizing the “Chance to Dance - Dance Party” for students enrolled in self-contained special education classes. At the dance party, participants interacted with their peers in a low pressure and fun social atmosphere. The activities at the dance also allowed students to meet important educational and social goals in an authentic environment. Two hundred students and fifty supervising adults attended the event from Clinton, Marion, Washington, Bond, Fayette and Jefferson Counties on October 23, 2019. The dance party was a positive and truly memorable event for the students and adults that attended.

Way to Go Mrs. Weh!!

--
Dr. Dustin Foutch
Superintendent, Central Community High School
It's Great to be a Cougar!!
#imaginegreatness

To all parents of 8th grade students:

As a reminder, Central CHS will be hosting our Freshman Registration Night on Wednesday, March 4, 2020 from 3:00pm -7:00pm. Also, if your child will potentially be attending Central next year and you were unable to attend our 8th grade information night, please don't hesitate to reach out to us. Our phone number is 618-526-4578 or you can email cchs@centralcougars.org

Thank you!

CCHS Student Council Project helps local parents in need.

Student Council sponsored a DOORS - DIAPERS - DOLLARS - DONUTS contest this week. Teachers decorated their classroom DOORS for Christmas and on Friday December 13th, the Student Council collected "DOLLAR Votes" for the best decorated door. The winning class received DONUTS during their 2nd hour exam review, and all dollars collected were used to purchase diapers and pull-ups for the Community Link parent store.Community Link provides supplies to parents and children and their store was in need of Diapers and Pull Ups to stock the shelves.

﻿The winning door was Mrs Ringwald's door & 2nd place was Mr. Peters door. Over 2,000 total diapers and pull-ups were collected to be donated to the community link Parent Store.

Way to Go CCHS Student Council!!

Central High School would like to thank the community for the generous donations of items to our Central Supply Store and Clothing Closet. We are fortunate to live in such a giving community. We continue to be contacted about what items we may be most in need of so we would like to share a list of things that we feel would be beneficial right now:

Men's personal care items - shampoo, body wash/soap, deodorant
Men's gently used clothing - pants, jeans, sweatpants, long sleeve shirts, hoodies - ALL sizes
Men's and women's colder weather shoes - tennis shoes, slip-ons etc, boots
Undergarments for men and women - new - all sizes
Socks - men and women - short to knee lengths
Coats - men and women - all sizes

Food items -
Snack food - granola bars, chips, fruit snacks, cookies, crackers, fruit cups
Breakfast - cereal bars, pop tarts

All items can be brought to the main office at Central or contact the school (526-4578), Mrs. Boruff (Ext 218) or Mrs. Benhoff (Ext 275) if needing items to be picked up. Thanks again. We could not do this without you.

post_text: Mr. Meyer's Psychology class has been working in a Brain and Behavior unit. In the unit they are learning about parts of the brains and their functions. Also, about how the functions of the brain alter and change behavior. For the project pictured students were required to research the lobes of the brain and what they allow the human body to do. Then, the students created a "brain hat" to represent a human brain.

post_text: CONGRATULATIONS to Blake Markus for being the 2019 FFA State Winner in Surveying. He won the event yesterday at Parkland College by defeating 25 other Section Surveying winners, one from each FFA Section in Illinois. Blake won with a score of 96 out of 100 points with a student from Prairie Central finishing second with 95 points.
text: CONGRATULATIONS to Blake Markus for being the 2019 FFA State Winner in Surveying. He won the event yesterday at Parkland College by defeating 25 other Section Surveying winners, one from each FFA Section in Illinois. Blake won with a score of 96 out of 100 points with a student from Prairie Central finishing second with 95 points.

Wow!!! We are completely BLOWN AWAY by the incredible fundraising efforts and enthusiasm we received from Central Community High School District #71 and Albers Elementary SD#63 during the week of World Down Syndrome Day -- they raised $1,845.62 collectively, with Albers coming in first at $1,066.40 and Central with $779.22.

We cannot say THANK YOU enough to these two schools -- the administrators, the teachers, and the students who made this all possible!! Thank you for making these contributions to our Community Link Buddy Walk, and thank you for advocating for people with Down syndrome and other disabilities. You are an inspiration and an example of what is possible when we all work together to make amazing things happen!!

Be sure to sign up for our Buddy Walk by April 5 to get a t-shirt with our NEW logo!

AGRICULTURE INSTRUCTOR / FFA SPONSOR

Position available for the 2019-20 school year. Applicants must hold Illinois Secondary Educator License with Agriculture Education Endorsement. NON-CERTIFIED VACANCIES

TECHNOLOGY DIRECTOR

Central Community High School is accepting applications for the position of Technology Director.

The position provides technological leadership and assistance for a wide range of issues including; communicating the school’s vision for technology, leading
technology team in planning and achieving goals, maintaining administrative and instructional computer systems, integrating software throughout the school, coordinating technology systems, and providing technology related professional development. The job
description, list of qualifications, and other information about the position can be obtained in the school office between the hours of 8:00 A.M. to 4:00 P.M. or by calling
526-4510. Please include letter of application, resume, transcripts, and any other related materials with application packet.

Apply by FRIDAY, MARCH 1, 2019 to:

Phone (618) 526-4510
